I will say this film is the best interactive cast from all his films, it keeps one engaged and I don''t find it to be filled with complexities because unlike other films there is no theoretical physics, or even psychology. Unless one has "telepathy" there''s no way to know exactly what''s going on inside another persons mind in imagery. Even ourselves when we dream it has to be intense, and written immediately most of us know we had a dream and the feeling but not the details of the dream.
The component of the brain that is active during REM sleep (when we dream) is also totally unrelated to memories. So geographically accessing memory, vocabulary, anything we know off hand is accessible pending a neurological disorder.
So the entire basic concept of the film has more wholes than "The Matrix".
So to enjoy this film you must suspend your thinking process...the other Nolan films compel the mind to try to figure out chronology why it was ordered that way and the human condition.
To me the Cob memory of Mal and his inability to let go of her is the main problem that Cob has. Assuming she ever existed or his children, because the writers dreamt up the script. There''s nothing in physics or psychology that would make one try to make sense..
The only reconciliation is his conscious memories of Mal which should be harmless, and his subconscious guilt over Mal ergo her chronic attempts to sabotage him. Because his guilt stems from was she correct in the fact that they were in a dream or was he correct that they weren''t. Like any untimely death or separation all humans are plagued with a level of guilt and at times turn to escapism to deal with the loss..in death visiting the grave frequently, in divorce or break ups clinging to pictures or memories of the good times, and in the more extreme Alcohol, Drugs or psychotropics. People when depressed or traumatized from loss typically have difficulty sleeping, not self loathing that creates apathy and excessive sleep.
I found the Cinematography, the Sound mixing, and the Cast as a unit phenomenal. I found it very entertaining by focusing on the attempted corporate espionage and ignoring the sleeping aspect and dream levels and viewing the process like a basketball or football game accomplishing a mission contingent on time.
I found the chemist though small in role interesting as it reminded me of an opium den...if you have time to research opium dens and the difference bt the type of pipe utilized and the composite it has the same withdrawal as opiates but it creates very vivid dream states of the past and present and people who have experienced claiming visions of a possible future based on the present and historical events.
But having a subconscious army, to see vivid geography, etc...you just have to sit back and enjoy like a Die Hard Film, or Bond.
Outside the internal conflict about Mal, I took this in as an espionage film without being bombarded by the "Dreaming Component". There''s actually a phenomenal parody of this film and VR devices like the Oculus in 06/07 South Park.
Just by doing a search the amount of discourse and dialogue wasted trying to breakdown this film deserved a parody...As they did with GOT, and LOTR.
Summation Phenomenal action Film and fun without trying to intellectualize it.', '12 January 2021');
One of the most celebrated and acclaimed movies of all time is a damn masterpiece.Pulp fiction is one of my favourite films ever and for good reason:
-the amazingly genius nonlinear story telling
-one of the most enjoyable performances of all time from Samuel l. Jackson.
-and of course the dialogueLook, as someone who has seen all of Quentin Tarantino''s great contributions to cinema history I can officially declare Pulp Fiction is still his best. After more than 25 years of being endlessly copied but never replicated there''s a reason people still watch this movie so often.It''s just so good.', '21 October 2020');
As many of you would know this movie is sort of like a tribute to the pulp stories written back in the 40s and 50s which have punchy and witty dialogue and over the top violence. The random chit chat between characters regarding obscure things might feel a waste of time as it doesn''t move the plot. But Tarantino is a genius and he believes in character development more than plot development so these chats actually humanizes the characters a lot and makes them relatable and memorable(The absolute converse of Nolan). This movie is just a collection of wonderful scenes back to back from start to finish.. The movie is a must watch just for the awesome screenplay alone. To top it off all the actors arguably give their career best performance(think about it ,it is true) . And the ability of Tarantino to just create a really tense or ridiculous situation out of nowhere(like the psycho tribute scene with marsellus and butch which is so unexpected or that adrenaline shot scene) is just awesome and keeps you on the edge of your seats .So if you want an entertaining but clever movie this is the one you are looking for . It is funny, filled with some of the best dialogues ever ,superbly acted, great soundtracks(I just wanna see Tarantino''s ipod , boy does he have great taste) and is just a spectacular experience.Spoilers ahead(duh):
For those of you who say the characters are hollow I suggest you to revisit the gold watch sequence. Walken''s Capt Koons tells a story to young butch about how Butch''s grandpa requested an enemy soldier to return his watch to his family and the soldier agreed. Similarly Butch could have left Marsellus but the legacy of his watch made him save him which I believe was a nice touch. And how Jules(one of my characters of all time) undergoes a change is also a noteworthy counter argument to the above mentioned criticism.Sorry for the huge review..', '10 April 2020');
